              subtype="transcription"
              xml:id="iopp0002.transcription"
              corresp="#iopp0002.diplomatic #iopp0002.translation">
            <p>Τόπος τὸν ἠγόρασα <lb/>ἐγὼ Νόννος</p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation"
              ana="#b1"
              xml:id="iopp0002.translation"
              corresp="#iopp0002.diplomatic #iopp0002.transcription">
            <p>This is the burial-place which I, Nonnos, bought.</p>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>Yellow-white limestone slab with a curved top found in Ioppe. The inscription is a declaration of the ownership of this burial site by (the presumably Jewish) Nonnos. This sort of inscription is paralleled in both Jewish and non-Jewish epigraphy. The word ἠγόρασα (ἀγοράζειν) is clearly used in this and other inscriptions to indicate legal ownership. It is uncertain as to whether or not someone was buried inside when this inscription was erected. A palm branch is engraved at the end of the second line of the inscription. The editor notes that the name Nonnos is attested in a number of other inscriptions, Jewish and otherwise. The inscription makes use of lunate sigmas and large minuscule omegas (rather than majuscule ones).</p>
         </div>
